AMRE.text: A distinctive clear V-like call, with a leveling out after the dip, and without the modulation of a BAWW.

BAWW.text:
BAWW NFCs are generally distinctive and easy to identify. They are two-parted, with a dip in the beginning and a level area at the end. Ruling out similar species follows this rubric:
(1) Two parted (rules out NOWA, LOWA, KEWA, CSWA). If two-partedness does not involve tail, rules out BWWA. If two-partedness does not include modulation changes, rules out GWWA.
(2) Wavelength under 4.1mS (rules out NOWA, LOWA, KEWA, CSWA)
(3) More than 10 waves (rules out NOWA, LOWA, BLPW, KEWA).

BBWA.text: Bay-breasted Warblers have a tseep-like call, with two humps, level or slightly descending, with a wavelength of 19mS+, a frequency of 7.2±.6kHz, single- or lightly double-banded, length of 60±10mS, unless otherwise noted. Landsborough (2017) found BBWA was the only warbler in the tseep complex which gave a call over 19mS in wavelength.

BTBW.text: Black-throated Blue Warblers tend to have a distinctive upward shooting flight call, with a small kink in the middle. It generally is delivered alone.

CAWA.text: Canada Warblers have a distinctively shaped call, with an initial V dropping down to 4kHz~, then leveling out to 6.5k±5Hz, with light modulation with a depth of 750Hz~ and two to five humps. Any depth of the V less than 3.4kHz can rule out WIWA and COYE, and a length longer than 40mS can rule out WIWA.

CMWA.text: Cape May Warblers are noted as having a concave downward descending call, with 5-6 humps, an average of 10mS wavelength, duration of 50±10mS, and modulation depth of 300-600Hz, unless noted. Distinctive given wavelength and shape.

CSWA.text: Chestnut-sided Warblers have a level flight call around 80ms in length with 8-10 period peaks. It seems to look superficially like Indigo Bunting and some of the other zeep calls, but is more regular and single-banded.

INBU.text: A double-banded long call at around 7kHz, with a height of round 2kHz.

NOPA.text: A high call that can have a slight kink, and is deeper in frequency than Pine Warbler, often with a initial ascender.

OVEN.text: All OVEN calls level out at 7±.5kHz, with 4-6 modulations, with a short descent and fast ascent to a level area, causing the distinctive "tadpole tail", and are single banded.

SAVS.text: A double-banded descending sparrow call, without the long even-out of a SOSP.

WIWA.text: WIWA generally have a 40mS call but with a clear inverted V shape with an initial rising section. Depths from 4.7-8.4kHz. Slightly double-banded, without even modulation. Given diurnally as well as nocturnally. The closest similar call would be Canada Warbler with an inverted V followed by a flat modulated section. Distictive given shape and length.

PARULIDAE.text: Automatically classified by BirdVox 0.6.0, and visually inspected by me.

PASSERIFORMES.text: Automatically classified by BirdVox 0.6.0, and visually inspected by me.

SWSP_LISP.text: Swamp Sparrow and Lincoln's Sparrow are difficult to tell apart, and it seemed safest to just call it a split here. The call is a relatively long sparrow call with a lot of modulations - like 25 or so - over around .75 seconds, in two bands hovering at around 7kHz.
